11 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY Section 2, Chapter 492, O.S.L.
12 2025 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 1210.900), is amended to read as
13 follows:
14 Section 1210.900. A. Sections 2 This section through 8 Section
15 1210.907 of this act title shall be known and may be cited as the
16 “Oklahoma Math Achievement and Proficiency Act”.
17 B. The Legislature finds that it is essential for children
18 enrolled in the public schools in this state to develop strong
19 mathematical proficiency early and consistently. The Legislature
20 further finds that clear and visible goals, assessments to determine
21 math proficiency at each school, the use of scientifically based and
22 researched methodologies in math instruction, along with regular and
23 periodic measurements of school math improvement, and accountability
24 at each level of the educational system will result in a significant
Req. No. 3832 Page 10

1 incr ease in the number of children performing at or above grade
2 level in mathematics.
3 C. The purpose of the Oklahoma Math Achievement and Proficiency
4 Act is to ensure that student achievement in math is encouraged and
5 progression from one grade to another is determined, in part, upon
6 proficiency in mathematics, that school district board of education
7 policies facilitate promotion of advanced math instruction and
8 intervention services to address student math needs, and that each
9 student and his or her parent or legal guardian be informed of the
10 student’s progress in mathematics.
11 D. Each public school district in this state shall ensure that
12 all students receive a well-rounded education focused on building
13 deep foundations in mathematics, reading, and writing. The State
14 Board of Education shall encourage school districts to integrate the
15 teaching of the other curricular areas in subject matter standards
16 adopted by the Board with the instruction of mathematics, reading,
17 and writing.
18 E. All teachers of mathematics in the public schools in this
19 state shall have access to training in evidence-based professional
20 development programs to deepen their content knowledge, learn
21 specific effective and impactful teaching strategies, and develop
22 productive dispositions toward math, and then incorporate into
23 instruction the foundational elements of math instruction, including
24 the development of grade-level appropriate mathematical proficiency
Req. No. 3832 Page 11

1 whic h is a combination of real-world problem-solving skills,
2 procedural fluency, conceptual understanding, and productive
3 dispositions.
4 F. 1. There is hereby created within the State Department of
5 Education an Office of Mathematics Improvement, which shall be
6 created within ninety (90) days of the effective date of this act.
7 The Superintendent of Public Instruction shall appoint a Director of
8 the Office of Mathematics Improvement whose exclusive focus shall be
9 mathematics instruction for students in grades kindergarten through
10 five. The Director shall have experience in administrative duties,
11 in teaching mathematics in a public or private elementary school,
12 and as an elementary mathematics specialist, coach, or
13 administrator.
14 2. The Director of the Office of Mathematics Improvement shall:
15 a. monitor implementation of screening instruments,
16 diagnostic assessments, and formative assessments for
17 grades kindergarten through five to identify students
18 in need of support for key numeracy concepts,
19 b. recommend training and support for educators for the
20 effective implementation and interpretation of
21 diagnostic tools. The diagnostic tool shall be used
22 with students who have been identified with
23 deficiencies in mathematics based on screening
24 instruments, diagnostic assessments, formative
Req. No. 3832 Page 12

1 assessments, benchmark assessments, teacher
2 observation, or any combination thereof,
3 c. designate a team of educators to explore the
4 connection between difficulties with number sense and
5 dyscalculia as well as possible effective screening
6 instruments,
7 d. commit necessary resources to understanding the needs
8 of students struggling with number sense or
9 dyscalculia, or both, before implementing
10 instructional practices or assessments that could
11 adversely affect student learning,
12 e. monitor the implementation and progress of summer
13 mathematics academies,
14 f. recommend changes and improvements to any professional
15 development providers and public schools in this state
16 based on data collected and analyzed by the Office of
17 Mathematics Improvement, and
18 g. monitor the implementation and progress of the
19 Oklahoma Math Achievement and Proficiency Act.
20 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY Section 3, Chapter 492, O.S.L.
21 2025 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 1210.901), is amended to read as
22 follows:
23 Section 1210.901. A. To identify students who have a math
24 deficiency including students with characteristics of dyscalculia,
Req. No. 3832 Page 13

1 each student enrolled in second, third, fourth, and fifth grade in a
2 public school in this state shall be screened at the beginning,
3 middle, and end of each school year for math proficiency including,
4 but not limited to, real-world problem-solving skills, procedural
5 fluency, conceptual understanding, and productive dispositions. A
6 screening instrument approved by the State Board of Education shall
7 be utilized for the purposes of this section. In determining which
8 screening instrument to approve, the State Board of Education shall
9 take into consideration, at a minimum, the following factors:
10 1. The time required to conduct the screening instrument with
11 the intention of minimizing the impact on instructional time;
12 2. The timeliness in reporting screening instrument results to
13 teachers, administrators, and parents or legal guardians of
14 students; and
15 3. The integration of the screening instrument into the math
16 curriculum.
17 B. Beginning in the 2026-2027 2027-2028 school year, the State
18 Board of Education shall approve a list of three screening
19 instruments for use at the beginning, middle, and end of the school
20 year for monitoring progress and measurement of math proficiency as
21 required in subsection A of this section. The screening instruments
22 shall be chosen from a list of recommendations from the Office of
23 Mathematics Improvement within the State Department of Education.
24 The screening instrument shall:
Req. No. 3832 Page 14

1 1. Assess mathematical proficiency, which is a combination of
2 real-world problem-solving skills, procedural fluency, conceptual
3 understanding, and productive dispositions for the grade level as
4 defined by the state’s subject matter standards;
5 2. Document the validity and reliability of each assessment;
6 3. Be used for identifying students who are at risk for math
7 deficiencies and for progress monitoring throughout the school year;
8 4. Be used to assess students with disabilities and English
9 language learners; and
10 5. Be accompanied by a data management system that provides
11 profiles of students, class, grade level, and school building. The
12 profiles shall identify each student’s instructional point of need,
13 competency for advanced math coursework, and math proficiency level.
14 The State Board of Education shall also determine other comparable
15 math assessments for diagnostic purposes to be used for students at
16 risk of math failure.
17 C. 1. Exemptions to the screening requirements required by
18 this section may be provided to students who have documented
19 evidence that they meet at least one of the following criteria as
