12 SECTION 4. AMENDATORY Section 4, Chapter 492, O.S.L.
13 2025 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 1210.902), is amended to read as
14 follows:
15 Section 1210.902. A. Contingent on the provision of
16 appropriated funds designated for the Oklahoma Math Achievement and
17 Proficiency Act, public school districts may be allocated monies for
18 each enrolled second-, third-, fourth-, and fifth-grade student of
19 the current school year who is found to be in need of remediation or
20 intensive intervention services in mathematics. The allocation
21 shall be distributed to each public school district upon approval of
22 the strong math plan for the school district by the State Board of
23 Education and the submittal of a child-count report to the State
24 Department of Education that details the number of students
Req. No. 3832 Page 20

1 iden tified as needing remediation or intensive intervention services
2 in mathematics. To determine a per-student allocation amount, the
3 total amount of funds available for allocation each year shall be
4 divided by the total number of students in the state identified as
5 in need of remediation or intensive intervention services in
6 mathematics as provided for in Section 3 1210.901 of this act title.
7 Each public school district shall be allocated an amount equal to
8 the per-student allocation amount multiplied by the number of
9 identified students enrolled in the school district.
10 B. Public school districts receiving more than Two Thousand
11 Five Hundred Dollars ($2,500.00) pursuant to subsection A of this
12 section shall spend no less than ten percent (10%) to provide
13 professional development for teachers. The professional development
14 shall include training in scientifically based math research
15 including how students learn mathematical concepts; training in
16 providing explicit and systematic instruction in real-world problem-
17 solving skills, procedural fluency, conceptual understanding, and
18 productive dispositions; implementing math strategies that research
19 has shown to be successful in improving math proficiency among
20 students with math difficulties; courses leading to a micro-
21 credential in mathematics; and instructional materials required for
22 implementation.
23 C. The Office of Mathematics Improvement within the State
24 Department of Education shall approve and publish a list of
Req. No. 3832 Page 21

1 prof essional development programs and providers that are evidence-
2 based and directly address the cognitive science of how students
3 learn mathematics for which districts are permitted to use the funds
4 received pursuant to this section.
5 D. If a teacher attends and completes a professional
6 development institute in elementary math approved by the Commission
7 for Educational Quality and Accountability during the summer or when
8 school is not in session, the teacher may receive a stipend equal to
9 the amount of the cost for a substitute teacher, based on the amount
10 of funds allocated.
